# plotting and image tools import seaborn as sns import matplotlib.pyplot as plt from matplotlib.patches import PathPatch from matplotlib.offsetbox import OffsetImage, AnnotationBbox import numpy as np from PIL import Image # shiny express for app interface from shiny import reactive, render from shiny.express import input, render, ui # from plots import bearpieplot # load mathjax to render latex, etc # info from here: https://www.fabriziomusacchio.com/blog/2021-08-10-How_to_use_LaTeX_in_Markdown/ ui.HTML('''''') # assuming that cub is 0-1 years # juvinile is 1-4 years # adult is 4+ years # title ui.page_opts(title="Modeling the Utah Black Bear Population with Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors", fillable=True) # footer = ?? # IMGS = {"matrix" : } # image # ui.setBackgroundImage(src = "image1.jpg") # add sidebar with ui.sidebar(open="desktop"): with ui.tooltip(id="ss2_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "ss2", "Juvenile Stasis (ss2)", min=0, max=100, value=50, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living, juvenile bears in a given year that are still living, juvenile bears in the next" # https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/#:~:text=Two%20of%20the%20biggest%20threats,of%20a%20new%20home%20range. # yearling mortality is 1/4 per year on average similar or greater for older juviniles it seems # adulthood is 'about 4 years old' # we'll assume 0.25 juvenile mortality since this seems more typical for females, and then since juveniles are from 1 year to 4 years, it takes them 3 years to mature, so if it weren't for mortality, about 1/3 or 0.33 would mature every year, or 0.67 don't. So probability of survival is 0.75 and probability of remaining a juvinile is 0.67 so our probability of stasis assuming these are independent is 0.75*0.67\approx 0.5. with ui.tooltip(id="ss3_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "ss3", "Adult Stasis (ss3)", min=0, max=100, value=93, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living, adult bears in a given year that are still living, adult bears in the next" # average lifespan is 18 years: https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=American_black_bear&oldid=1227551752 # another article (https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/#:~:text=Two%20of%20the%20biggest%20threats,of%20a%20new%20home%20range.) says that adulthood is about 4 years # adult for 14 of those years say, then let’s assume an exponential mortality curve, so the exponent is -1/14 and then that means that the adult stasis value should be exp(-1/14) \approx 0.9310627797. with ui.tooltip(id="sm1_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "sm1", "Cub maturation (sm1)", min=0, max=100, value=65, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living cubs in a given year that become living juvenile bears in the next" # https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/ # cub mortality is 25-50% # we'll average 35%, then maturation should be 65% with ui.tooltip(id="sm2_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "sm2", "Juvenile maturation (sm2)", min=0, max=100, value=25, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The fraction of living juvenile bears in a given year that become living adult bears in the next" # https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/#:~:text=Two%20of%20the%20biggest%20threats,of%20a%20new%20home%20range. # yearling mortality is 1/4 per year on average similar or greater for older juviniles it seems # adulthood is 'about 4 years old' # we'll assume 0.25 juvenile mortality since this seems more typical for females, and then since juveniles are from 1 year to 4 years, it takes them 3 years to mature, so if it weren't for mortality, about 1/3 or 0.33 would mature every year, or 0.67 don't. So probability of survival is 0.75 and probability of maturing is 0.33 so our probability of maturation assuming these are independent is 0.75*0.67\approx 0.25. with ui.tooltip(id="f3_tooltip", placement="right"): ui.input_slider( "f3", "Fecundity (f3)", min=0, max=100, value=20, step=1, post="%" # pre="", ) ui.HTML("""
""") "The average number of cubs that are produced in a given year per living adult bear, expressed as a percentage" # fecundity seems somewhat variable # the poster cited below predicts that the bear population in utah is stable, so I'll choose a value that reflects this based on the other parameters # 0.20 seems to be a good number based on the slider to reflect the poster's predicted growth rate of 0.97 ui.markdown(""" A population is a group of organisms, like people or bears, that live in the same area and interbreed. Population dynamics is the study of how a population changes over time, including the numbers and ages of the organisms in the population. Try adjusting the values in the sidebar to see how this changes the ratio of bear cubs, juveniles, and adult bears, as well as the growth or decay of the population over time. Scroll to the bottom to see the linear algebra behind these graphics! """) with ui.layout_columns(fill=False): with ui.value_box(): ui.markdown( """ Population distribution """ ) # long term predicted population dist. @render.express def peigvec(): eigvec = np.round(pevec()/np.sum(pevec()), decimals=2) streigvec = str(list(eigvec)) ui.markdown( "**v**_1 = " + streigvec + "^T") @render.plot def pie(): labels = ["Cubs", "Juveniles", "Adults"] total = pevec() ax = plt.gca() # plt.title("Long term population distribution") plt.title("Utah Black Bear Demographics") ax.axis("equal") # Fill in a pie chart with images. adopted from # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44528024/insert-image-into-pie-chart-slice # total = [5,7,4] # plt.title('Bears') # plt.gca().axis("equal") # plot a colored pie chart in the background ax.pie(total, startangle=90) wedges, texts = ax.pie(total, startangle=90, labels=labels, wedgeprops = { 'linewidth': 1, "edgecolor" :"k","fill":False, }) # find the bisecting vector of each pie wedge as an angle from (1, 0) in radians centroids = np.pi/2 + 2 * np.pi * np.array([(sum(total[:i]) + total[i]/2)/sum(total) for i, tot in enumerate(total)]) # get the x, y for these vectors (but only half of the length so that the images end up within the slices) # rows are the three images and columns are x vs y positions = np.stack([np.cos(centroids), np.sin(centroids)]).T/2 # adjust image zoom zooms = [0.4,0.4,0.4] for i in range(3): # get the filename for the respective image filename = "{}.jpg".format(labels[i]) # read in image files im = None if filename=="Adults.jpg": im = imadults() elif filename=="Cubs.jpg": im = imcubs() elif filename=="Juveniles.jpg": im = imjuveniles() # get the path? to the respective wedge of the pie chart and begin plotting there path = wedges[i].get_path() patch = PathPatch(path, facecolor='none') ax.add_patch(patch) # place image at the respective locations and clip using the wedge (?) imagebox = OffsetImage(im, zoom=zooms[i], clip_path=patch, zorder=-10) ab = AnnotationBbox(imagebox, positions[i], xycoords='data', pad=0, frameon=False) ax.add_artist(ab) # overlay the clip so that for sure the images get clipped into the wedges wedges[i].set_zorder(10) ui.markdown( """ The **principal eigenvector** of the transition matrix represents the age distribution the population will approach over time. The age distribution of the population should naturally approach this ratio as time goes on. """ ) with ui.value_box(): ui.markdown( """ Population growth """ ) # long term predicted population growth @render.express def peigval(): "λ_1 = " + str(np.round(peval(), decimals=2)) @render.plot def pred(): x, y = prediction() # convert x value to current years from datetime import date year_ = date.today().year plt.plot(x+year_, y, 'go-') plt.ylim(bottom=0, top=max(3000, y[4])) plt.ylabel("Predicted population size") plt.xlabel("year") plt.title("Utah Black Bear Count") ax = plt.gca() # ax.title("Long term population growth") ui.markdown( """ The **principal eigenvalue** of the transition matrix represents the maximum growth rate of the population. When the age breakdown doesn't match the principal eigenvector, the overall growth rate may be inconsistent, or lower than the predicted rate. """ ) with ui.layout_columns(fill=False): with ui.value_box(): "Definitions" # having trouble centering, so I'm just using matplotlib @render.plot def mplimgplot2(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent img = np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "mymath.png"))) # print(img) # print(img.shape) # draw image myplot = plt.imshow(img) ax = plt.gca() ax.axis('off') return myplot ui.markdown( """ The **principal eigenvalue** of the transition matrix is the eigenvalue with the largest absolute value. The **principal eigenvector** is the eigenvector associated with this eigenvalue. """ ) # render an image standalone # @render.image # def image(): # from pathlib import Path # dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent # img = {"src": str(dir / "mymath.png"), "width": "100%"} # return img with ui.value_box(): "Transition matrix" # @render.express # def value(): # input.alpha_val() @render.plot def mplimgplot(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent img = np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "modified_mymatrix.png"))) # print(img) # print(img.shape) # draw image myplot = plt.imshow(img) # specify axes ax = plt.gca() # plot values in left matrix # values for easy adjustment dx = 512 dy = 280 w = 175 h = w # # for mymatrix.png: # dx = 100 # dy = 125 # w = 175 # h = w # row 1 ax.text(0*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '$ss_1$') ax.text(1*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '$f_2$') ax.text(2*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '$f_3$') # row 2 ax.text(0*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '$sm_1$') ax.text(1*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '$ss_2$') ax.text(2*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '0') # row 3 ax.text(0*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '0') ax.text(1*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '$sm_2$') ax.text(2*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '$ss_3$') # plot numbers in right matrix # values for easy adjustment dx = 1230 dy = 280 # w = 175 # h = w # row 1 ax.text(0*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '0') ax.text(1*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '0') ax.text(2*w+dx, 0*h+dy, '.' + str(input.f3())) # row 2 ax.text(0*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '.' + str(input.sm1())) ax.text(1*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '.' + str(input.ss2())) ax.text(2*w+dx, 1*h+dy, '0') # row 3 ax.text(0*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '0') ax.text(1*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '.' + str(input.sm2())) ax.text(2*w+dx, 2*h+dy, '.' + str(input.ss3())) # final adjustments # remove axes ax.axis('off') return myplot ui.markdown( """ Our **transition matrix** has all non-negative real values. By the [Perron-Frobenius theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perron%E2%80%93Frobenius_theorem), this implies that, the principal eigenvalue and each entry in the principal eigenvector will also be non-negative eral numbers. """ ) ui.markdown( """ Populations can be modeled using linear algebra. Here we are considering a population of bears. Since bear cubs, juvenile bears, and adult bears all behave differently, we are modeling them as separate categories of bears. - Transition matrix - Principal eigenvector - Perron-Frobenius theorem Inspired by work from Brenden Orocu, Dr. Mark Belk, and others, on modeling black bear populations in eastern Utah: https://byu.app.box.com/s/typ96vcpp010vyytqkufpd1qptcnldh3 Images and demographic information for the default parameter estimates came from the following sources: “American Black Bear.” 2024. In Wikipedia. https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=American_black_bear&oldid=1227551752. Animals are Awesome, dir. 2017. Baby Black Bear Cubs Playing Compilation. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2cj5pPe778. “Black Bear | Size, Weight, Habitat, Diet, & Facts | Britannica.” n.d. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://www.britannica.com/animal/black-bear. “Facts about Florida Black Bears: Life Expectancy.” n.d.-a. Florida Fish And Wildlife Conservation Commission. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/. “———.” n.d.-b. Florida Fish And Wildlife Conservation Commission. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/. KUTV, Sara Knox. 2021. “Utah’s Drought May Lead to More Aggressive Black Bears.” KUTV. May 18, 2021. https://kutv.com/news/local/utahs-drought-may-lead-to-more-aggressive-black-bears. Schnee (KUTV), Brian. 2024. “Biologists Checking on Utah’s Healthy Bear Population, Visiting Dens across the State.” KUTV. March 19, 2024. https://kutv.com/news/local/utah-biologists-checking-on-bear-dens-across-the-state-dwr-wildlife. """ ) # # render an image standalone # @render.image # def image(): # from pathlib import Path # dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent # img = {"src": str(dir / "mymatrix.png"), "width": "100px"} # return img # -------------------------------------------------------- # Reactive calculations and effects # -------------------------------------------------------- # linear algebra @reactive.calc def transition_matrix(): return np.array([ [0, 0, input.f3()], [input.sm1(), input.ss2(), 0], [0, input.sm2(), input.ss3()] ])/100 @reactive.calc def eigs(): return np.linalg.eig(transition_matrix()) @reactive.calc def prineigs(): # print(eigs()) evals = eigs()[0] evecs = eigs()[1] i = np.argmax(evals) return (np.abs(evals[i]), np.abs(evecs[:,i])) @reactive.calc def peval(): return prineigs()[0] @reactive.calc def pevec(): return prineigs()[1] # plotting population @reactive.calc def prediction(init_pop = 2000): # about 2000 black bears in Utah in 2024: # https://kutv.com/news/local/utah-biologists-checking-on-bear-dens-across-the-state-dwr-wildlife years = 5 x = np.array(range(years)) # make array full of peval() entries to raise to the power later pevalarr = peval()+np.zeros(years) return (x, init_pop*np.power(pevalarr, x)) # # helperfunctions # @reactive.calc # def myimg(filename): # if filename=="Adults.jpg": # return imadults() # elif filename=="Cubs.jpg": # return imcubs() # elif filename=="Juveniles.jpg": # return imjuveniles() @reactive.calc def imadults(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent return np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "Adults.jpg"))) @reactive.calc def imcubs(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent return np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "Cubs.jpg"))) @reactive.calc def imjuveniles(): from pathlib import Path dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent return np.asarray(Image.open(str(dir / "Juveniles.jpg"))) # elif filename=="Cubs.jpg": # im = imcubs() # elif filename=="Juveniles.jpg": # im = imjuveniles() # path = wedge.get_path() # patch = PathPatch(path, facecolor='none') # subax.add_patch(patch) # imagebox = OffsetImage(im, zoom=zoom, clip_path=patch, zorder=-10) #
